| [Belarus](/Belarus) | 11 March 2022, 7 April 2022 | | All versions | | Yes | The government of Belarus, under the authoritarian rule of [Alexander Lukashenka](/Alexander_Lukashenka), has taken severe measures against [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) editors, particularly those involved in documenting sensitive political events. On 11 March 2022, [GUBOPiK](/GUBOPiK), the Belarusian political police, arrested and detained [Mark Bernstein](/Detention_of_Mark_Bernstein), a prominent editor of the [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) residing in Minsk. His alleged crime was editing the article concerning the [Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine). He was accused of the "spread of anti-Russian materials" and, in a bizarre application of extraterritorial law, of violating Russian "fake news" laws. This incident highlighted the regime's willingness to crack down on independent information, even when it originates from a global, collaborative platform. This wasn't an isolated event; on 7 April 2022, a court in [Brest](/Brest,_Belarus) sentenced another [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) user, [Pavel Pernikaŭ](/Detention_of_Pavel_Pernika%C5%AD), to a two-year prison term. His conviction stemmed from three specific edits made to articles on both the [Russian](/Russian_Wikipedia) and [Belarusian Wikipedia](/Belarusian_Wikipedia). He was found guilty under Article 369-1 of the [Criminal Code of Belarus](/Criminal_Code_of_Belarus), which broadly criminalizes "discrediting the Republic of Belarus." These cases serve as a stark warning to any citizen contemplating contributing factual information that deviates from the state-sanctioned narrative. |
| [China](/China) | 2004, 2005–2008, 2015–present (https), April 2019–present (all) | All | All versions | Yes | Yes | The relationship between [China](/China) and [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has been, to put it mildly, fraught with conflict, evolving into a continuous cat-and-mouse game where the state consistently tries to assert its control over information. This long-standing struggle is well-documented under the broader umbrellas of [Wikimedia censorship in mainland China](/Wikimedia_censorship_in_mainland_China) and [Internet censorship in China](/Internet_censorship_in_China). Access to [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) within mainland China has fluctuated dramatically over the years, with the [Chinese Wikipedia](/Chinese_Wikipedia) typically facing far tighter restrictions than its counterparts in other languages. As of April 2019, the situation escalated to a full-scale blockade, with all versions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) being inaccessible in mainland China, effectively swallowed by the infamous [Great Firewall](/Great_Firewall). <br><br> The [Chinese Wikipedia](/Chinese_Wikipedia) itself was first launched in May 2001. Initially, it even received some positive, if cautious, coverage in China's state press in early 2004. However, this brief honeymoon ended abruptly on 3 June 2004, when the site was blocked. The timing was hardly coincidental, preceding the 15th anniversary of the [1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre](/1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre)—a date the Chinese government goes to extraordinary lengths to erase from public memory. In response, there were internal discussions within the Chinese Wikipedia community about whether to practice [self-censorship](/Self-censorship) as a means to restore access, but these proposals were ultimately rejected. Despite this, an investigation by the [International Herald Tribune](/International_Herald_Tribune) revealed that Chinese entries on politically sensitive topics like [Mao Zedong](/Mao_Zedong) and [Taiwan](/Taiwan) were often "watered down and sanitized" of controversy, suggesting a subtle, pre-emptive form of content management. Access was briefly restored on 22 June 2004, only to be blocked again in September for four days, and then once more in October 2005. During this period, concerned users like Shi Zhao and Cui Wei wrote appeals to authorities, arguing that blocking [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) hindered China's ability to present its own voice and allowed "evil cults, [Taiwan independence](/Taiwan_independence_movement) forces and others...to present a distorted image of China." <br><br> In October 2006, [The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times) reported a curious development: the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia) appeared to be unblocked, while the Chinese version remained largely inaccessible. However, this "unblocking" was far from complete, as noted by [new media](/New_media) researcher [Andrew Lih](/Andrew_Lih), who found that he still couldn't access the English article on the Tiananmen Square protests. Lih also highlighted the non-uniform nature of the [Great Firewall](/Great_Firewall), observing that accessibility varied depending on the [internet service provider](/Internet_service_provider) and geographical location within China. [Reporters Without Borders](/Reporters_Without_Borders) commended [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s leadership for resisting [self-censorship](/Self-censorship) during this period. <br><br> A glimmer of hope emerged on 10 November 2006, when Lih reported that the [Chinese Wikipedia](/Chinese_Wikipedia) seemed to have been fully unblocked. This was quickly confirmed, and the effects were immediate and dramatic: the rate of new account creation more than tripled, and article creation surged by 75%, making it the second fastest-growing [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) after the English version. Lih optimistically predicted rapid growth but also noted the challenge of integrating so many new users into [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s established policies and norms. However, this openness was fleeting. By 16 November 2006, [Reuters](/Reuters) reported that while the main page was accessible, articles on "taboo political subjects," such as "4 June, 1989 protests," remained blocked. The very next day, 17 November, both the Chinese and English versions were reportedly reblocked. <br><br> The pattern of intermittent blocking and unblocking continued. On 15 June 2007, non-political articles on the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia) were restored, only for the entire English version to be blocked again by 6 September 2007. Then, on 2 April 2008, [The Register](/The_Register) and [BBC](/BBC) reported that blocks on both English and Chinese Wikipedias were lifted, a move widely attributed to foreign journalists arriving in Beijing for the [2008 Summer Olympics](/2008_Summer_Olympics) and the [International Olympic Committee](/International_Olympic_Committee)'s demand for [press freedom](/Freedom_of_the_press) during the games. Following this, in September 2008, [Jimmy Wales](/Jimmy_Wales) met with [Cai Mingzhao](/Cai_Mingzhao), Vice Director of China's [State Council Information Office](/State_Council_Information_Office), hoping to open a channel of communication with the [government of China](/Government_of_China). <br><br> The academic community also took notice. A 2011 report in the [American Economic Review](/American_Economic_Review) found that the blocking of the [Chinese Wikipedia](/Chinese_Wikipedia) not only reduced its user base but also decreased the contributions of unblocked users by an average of 42.8%, illustrating the chilling effect of state censorship. <br><br> By 2012, both the Chinese and English Wikipedias were generally accessible, *except* for political articles. Any attempt to access or search for a "sensitive" article would result in a temporary block of the user's IP address from [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) for several minutes to an hour. This was a more sophisticated, albeit still frustrating, form of control. <br><br> The shift to secure [HTTPS](/HTTPS) connections, which began on 31 May 2013, presented a new challenge for Chinese authorities. While the non-secure [HTTP](/HTTP) version remained vulnerable to keyword filtering, [HTTPS](/HTTPS) made it harder to selectively block individual articles. [GreatFire](/GreatFire), an organization dedicated to circumventing Chinese censorship, urged [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) and its users to utilize other [IP addresses](/IP_address) owned by [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) with [HTTPS](/HTTPS) to bypass the block. Around this time, [Jimmy Wales](/Jimmy_Wales) famously declared that [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) would not tolerate "5 seconds" of censorship. This assertion was met with skepticism by some Chinese internet researchers, who suggested that [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) might be less defiant when faced with demands from Western governments. Meanwhile, a Chinese Wikipedia administrator, Huang, reported being under an exit ban by the government since 2009 without clear reason, demonstrating the personal cost of such work. <br><br> The cat-and-mouse game continued: GreatFire reported that both encrypted and unencrypted [Chinese Wikipedia](/Chinese_Wikipedia) were blocked on 19 May 2015. Since June 2015, all [Wikipedias](/List_of_Wikipedias) have redirected [HTTP](/HTTP) requests to [HTTPS](/HTTPS) addresses, making encryption mandatory. This rendered the entire site inaccessible in China, as censors could no longer identify and block specific pages like those on [Ai Weiwei](/Ai_Weiwei), [Liu Xiaobo](/Liu_Xiaobo), or [Tiananmen Square](/Tiananmen_Square). <br><br> In December 2015, [Jimmy Wales](/Jimmy_Wales) announced his intention to lobby the Chinese government to unblock the site. Coincidentally, or perhaps not, [China](/China) then completely blocked all language versions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) on 4 December. This led to widespread complaints on Chinese social networks, which were, predictably, quickly deleted. Access to other languages was briefly restored on 6 December. Wales later met with [Lu Wei](/Lu_Wei_(politician)), director of the [Cyberspace Administration of China](/Cyberspace_Administration_of_China), on 17 December 2015. Wales reiterated [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s stance against censorship, stating, "Never," when asked if he would compromise. The official translation of his remarks at the [World Internet Conference](/World_Internet_Conference) even saw his statement about machine translation making information control "no longer possible" warped into "help governments to better analyze online communications." <br><br> The most recent, and arguably most comprehensive, blockade began on 23 April 2019, when all versions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) were once again blocked in China. This move effectively cemented the [Great Firewall](/Great_Firewall)'s dominance over access to this global knowledge resource. <br><br> The conflict extended beyond simple blocking. On 23 September 2020, the Chinese government rejected Wikimedia's application for official observer status at the [World Intellectual Property Organization](/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization). China's representative claimed that Wikimedia's webpages contained "a large amount of content and disinformation in violation of [the] [One China](/One_China) principle" and that Wikimedia's Taiwan branch was "carrying out political activities...which could undermine the state's sovereignty and territorial integrity." This rejection was repeated on 5 October 2021. <br><br> The state's control even extended to individual citizens. On 24 October 2020, a Chinese citizen in [Zhoushan](/Zhoushan), Zhejiang, was penalized by local police for the "crime" of "illegally visiting Wikipedia." This incident underscored the personal risks involved in circumventing state censorship. <br><br> Perhaps the most unsettling development has been the alleged infiltration of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s editorial processes. Despite the blanket ban, some mainland Chinese users were granted IP block exemptions, leading to accusations that these users were recruited to promote the Chinese government's viewpoint and influence the election of pro-Beijing administrators. Academics have even suggested that "China urgently needs to encourage and train Chinese netizens to become Wikipedia platform opinion leaders and administrators...[who] can adhere to socialist values and form some core editorial teams." This strategy has led to significant clashes, particularly with Taiwanese editors, over content and even death threats against Taiwan's Wikipedian community. One Taiwanese editor speculated that this wasn't merely patriotic fervor but a "larger structural coordinated strategy the government has to manipulate these platforms" beyond [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), extending to sites like [Twitter](/Twitter) and [Facebook](/Facebook). <br><br> The group known as Wikimedians of Mainland China (WMC or WMCUG) has been at the center of these controversies. They reportedly threatened to report [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) editors to [Hong Kong's national security police](/Hong_Kong_Police_Force) hotline over the heavily disputed article on the "[2019–2020 Hong Kong protests](/2019%E2%80%932020_Hong_Kong_protests)," an article characterized by intense [edit warring](/List_of_edit_wars_on_Wikipedia). An anonymous Hong Kong-based editor noted that "Pro-Beijing people often remove content that is sympathetic to protests, such as tear gas being fired and images of barricades. They also add their own content," while accusing pro-Beijing editors of being "a lot more aggressive in churning out disinformation." <br><br> This culminated in a significant intervention by the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) on 13 September 2021, when it [banned](/2021_Wikimedia_Foundation_actions_on_the_Chinese_Wikipedia) seven [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) users and stripped twelve members of the WMC of their administrator privileges. Maggie Dennis, the foundation's vice president of community resilience and sustainability, stated that a year-long investigation into "infiltration concerns" had revealed threats to the "very foundations of Wikipedia." Dennis explicitly linked the infiltrators to attempts to promote "the aims of China, as interpreted through whatever filters they may bring to bear," suggesting possible ties to the [Chinese Communist Party](/Chinese_Communist_Party). She emphasized the need to act based on "credible information that some members (not all) of that group [WMC] have harassed, intimidated, and threatened other members of our community, including in some cases physically harming others, in order to secure their own power and subvert the collaborative nature of our projects." It seems the battle for information isn't just external; it's an internal struggle for the integrity of the platform itself. |
| [India](/India) | July 2024, 21 October 2024, 17 March 2025, 9 May 2025 | | Select pages | | | The saga of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) in [India](/India) presents a fascinating, if somewhat convoluted, illustration of the tensions between digital freedom and national legal systems, particularly concerning issues of alleged [defamation](/Defamation) and judicial overreach. This is further detailed under [Internet censorship in India](/Internet_censorship_in_India). <br><br> In July 2024, [Asian News International](/Asian_News_International) (ANI), a prominent Indian news agency, initiated legal proceedings against the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation). ANI [sued Wikimedia](/Asian_News_International_vs._Wikimedia_Foundation) with the explicit aim of uncovering the identities of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) editors who had characterized the news agency as a "propaganda tool for the government" on the platform. ANI alleged that these editors had engaged in [defamation](/Defamation). The [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court) responded with a rather aggressive stance, threatening to block [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) across [India](/India) if the names of these editors were not divulged. This move sparked considerable debate about the court's jurisdiction over a global platform and the implications for editor anonymity. <br><br> The situation escalated dramatically on 21 October 2024, when the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) took the unprecedented step of suspending access to [the article for the lawsuit itself](/Asian_News_International_vs._Wikimedia_Foundation) on the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia). This action was taken in direct compliance with a court order from the [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court), which asserted that the article violated the [sub judice](/Sub_judice) principle—the legal rule preventing public discussion of cases still before a court. This marked a significant moment, believed to be the first instance of an English [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) page being taken down following a court order. <br><br> However, the legal narrative took another turn. On 17 March 2025, the [Supreme Court of India](/Supreme_Court_of_India), the country's highest judicial body, began to question the rationale behind the [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court)'s order. The Supreme Court notably asked why the High Court was being "so touchy" about the issue, further emphasizing that courts should not demand the removal of content merely because it is critical of them. Justices [Abhay S. Oka](/A._S._Oka) and [Ujjal Bhuyan](/Ujjal_Bhuyan) highlighted the profound implications of the case for [press freedom](/Freedom_of_the_press), stating, "This concerns press freedom. If it is Wikipedia today, it could be someone else tomorrow." <br><br> Ultimately, the [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court)'s order to remove the article was overturned on appeal to the [Supreme Court of India](/Supreme_Court_of_India). The Supreme Court delivered a decisive ruling, asserting that in a liberal democracy, the judiciary and media must operate in a mutually supportive manner, and it is not the role of the court to dictate content removal or takedown demands to the media. Consequently, on 9 May 2025, the article was restored, marking a significant victory for freedom of information and speech within the Indian legal landscape. |
| [Iran](/Iran) | 2013–2015 (partial), 2023–present (Wikinews) | Partial &#91; [failed verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) &#93; | Hundreds of articles | | | [Iran](/Iran)'s approach to [Internet censorship in Iran](/Internet_censorship_in_Iran) is a meticulously crafted digital curtain, and [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has consistently found itself caught in its folds. A detailed November 2013 report by researchers Collin Anderson and Nima Nazeri from the [Center for Global Communication Studies](/Center_for_Global_Communication_Studies) at the [University of Pennsylvania](/University_of_Pennsylvania) meticulously scanned 800,000 [Persian-language Wikipedia articles](/Persian_Wikipedia). Their findings were stark: the Iranian government had blocked 963 of these pages. The patterns of censorship were revealing, as the authors noted: "Censors repeatedly targeted Wikipedia pages about government rivals, minority religious beliefs, and criticisms of the state, officials, and the police." A significant portion—just under half—of these blocked pages were biographies, including those of individuals whom authorities had allegedly detained or killed. <br><br> Anderson insightfully observed that the [Persian Wikipedia](/Persian_Wikipedia), in its very nature, serves as a "useful place to uncover the types of online content forbidden and an excellent template to identify keyword blocking themes and filtering rules that apply across the greater internet." This highlights [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s unintended role as a barometer for state-controlled information. The censorship continued into May 2014, with [Mashable](/Mashable) reporting that at least two more pages on the [Persian Wikipedia](/Persian_Wikipedia) were blocked. <br><br> The disruptions to access were not limited to specific articles. During the height of the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic), access to [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) was reportedly disrupted across Iranian networks, as noted by the Associated Press. This suggests that even critical public health information, if not directly controlled, could become collateral damage in broader network interventions. As of 2023, [Wikinews](/Wikinews) Farsi remains blocked, and [XTools](/Wikipedia:XTools), a set of tools used by [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) editors for statistics and analysis, was also inaccessible for several months, further hindering the work of the editing community. This persistent, targeted censorship reveals a government deeply invested in shaping the information landscape available to its citizens, meticulously pruning away any narratives that challenge its authority or ideology. |
| [North Korea](/North_Korea) | | All | All versions | | | In [North Korea](/North_Korea), the concept of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) censorship is almost quaint, given the extreme isolation of the country. The entire [World Wide Web](/World_Wide_Web) is not merely filtered or selectively blocked; it is, for all practical purposes, physically disconnected from the vast majority of the population. Access to the global internet, and by extension, [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), is strictly limited to a minuscule elite within the government and military, and even then, under heavy surveillance. For the average citizen, the internet as the rest of the world knows it simply does not exist. Instead, they operate within a highly controlled national intranet, the Kwangmyong, which offers no access to outside information. Thus, [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) is not "blocked" in the conventional sense; it's simply beyond the reach of a society that has been deliberately cut off from the global information flow, making any discussion of specific article censorship moot in the face of absolute digital isolation. |
| [Myanmar](/Myanmar) | 15 February 2021 – present | All | All versions | | | Following the [military coup d'état](/2021_Myanmar_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat) on 1 February 2021, the junta in [Myanmar](/Myanmar) swiftly moved to consolidate its control over information, plunging the country into a digital blackout. On 21 February 2021, [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) was completely blocked in all languages, becoming another casualty of the military's aggressive [censorship](/Censorship regime. This comprehensive blockade meant that citizens were cut off from a vital source of independent information and global knowledge at a time when accurate news was most crucial. The move was part of a broader strategy to suppress dissent and control the narrative surrounding the coup, effectively isolating the population from external perspectives and internal organizing efforts. As of the latest reports, this blanket ban remains in place, reflecting the junta's ongoing efforts to maintain an iron grip on the flow of information. |
| [Pakistan](/Pakistan) | 31 March 2006, several days in May 2010, 3 February 2023 – 6 February 2023 | Partial | Some, all versions | | | [Pakistan](/Pakistan)'s history with [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) censorship is marked by intermittent, often religiously motivated, blocks, as part of its broader [Internet censorship in Pakistan](/Internet_censorship_in_Pakistan) policies. The first notable incident occurred on 31 March 2006, when the entire domain of wikipedia.org was blocked for a period of seven hours. The reason? A single article that contained information pertaining to the [controversial cartoons of Muhammad](/Jyllands-Posten_Muhammad_cartoons_controversy). This swift and comprehensive response demonstrated the authorities' sensitivity to content deemed blasphemous. <br><br> A few years later, in May 2010, the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia) was again blocked in [Pakistan](/Pakistan) for several days. This time, the ban was enacted amidst the controversy surrounding "Everybody Draw Mohammed Day](/Everybody_Draw_Mohammed_Day)," another event that sparked widespread outrage and demands for content removal. <br><br> The pattern re-emerged in early 2023, with a more dramatic escalation. On 1 February 2023, the [Pakistan Telecommunication Authority](/Pakistan_Telecommunication_Authority) (PTA) announced that it had "degraded" [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) services, effectively slowing access for 48 hours. The PTA's ultimatum was clear: if "sacrilegious content" was not removed, a full block would follow. When [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) did not comply, Pakistani authorities indeed blocked access to the platform on 3 February. This move was met with criticism from various quarters, highlighting the tension between religious sensitivities and freedom of information. <br><br> However, this block proved to be remarkably short-lived. On 6 February 2023, just three days after the ban was implemented, the Pakistani prime minister, [Shehbaz Sharif](/Shehbaz_Sharif), intervened. He ordered the PTA to immediately lift the ban on [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), stating that "Wikipedia was a useful site/portal which supported the dissemination of knowledge and information for the general public, students and the academia." This reversal underscored a pragmatic recognition of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s value, even in the face of contentious content. As of 15 June 2025 [[update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers)], most parts of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) are accessible, although [Wikimedia Commons](/Wikimedia_Commons), which hosts many of the images, remains inaccessible, suggesting a continued, albeit partial, effort to control certain types of content. <br><br> Wikinews has related news: <br> • Pakistan reverses block on Wikimedia projects, including Wikipedia |
| [Russia](/Russia) | 2010s–present &#91; [needs update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers) &#93; | Partial &#91; [needs update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers) &#93; | Select pages | Yes | Yes | The Russian government's relationship with [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has steadily deteriorated since the early 2010s, evolving into a systematic campaign of control and suppression, extensively documented in articles like [Block of Wikipedia in Russia](/Block_of_Wikipedia_in_Russia), [Disinformation in the Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Disinformation_in_the_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine), [Internet censorship in Russia](/Internet_censorship_in_Russia), [Mass surveillance in Russia](/Mass_surveillance_in_Russia), [Russian information war against Ukraine](/Russian_information_war_against_Ukraine), and [Wikipedia and the Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Wikipedia_and_the_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine). The [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) and its dedicated editors have faced an escalating barrage of threats, including the specter of [nationwide blocks](/Block_of_Wikipedia_in_Russia) and the country-wide enforcement of [blacklisting](/Blacklisting) by the [Russian government](/Government_of_Russia). These efforts have been accompanied by numerous attempts to [censor pages](/Internet_censorship), spread state-sanctioned [propaganda](/Internet_manipulation), and inject [disinformation](/Disinformation) into articles. This became particularly pronounced during the [2014 Russo-Ukrainian war in the Donbas region](/War_in_Donbas) and has intensified dramatically with the ongoing [Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine) since 2022. <br><br> The regulatory body, the [Federal Service for Supervision of Communications, Information Technology and Mass Media](/Roskomnadzor) (more commonly known as Roskomnadzor), confirmed [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s blacklisting on 5 April 2013, noting with a certain bureaucratic exasperation, "it had been 'for a long time. I don't know why it's only now that they've woken up'." On the same day, Roskomnadzor issued an order to the [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia): remove the article "Курение каннабиса" ("Cannabis smoking") or face a complete block of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) across [Russia](/Russia). The legal framework for such actions expanded significantly after a new law was passed around November 2013, granting the government broader powers to block content deemed illegal or harmful to children, a conveniently broad definition. <br><br> A more direct confrontation arose on 18 August 2015, when Roskomnadzor demanded that [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) administrators delete the article "Чарас (наркотическое вещество)" ("Charas (narcotic substance)"), which detailed the cannabis derivative [charas](/Charas), by 21 August. Failure to comply would result in a block, a threat they partially executed on 25 August. A Russian provincial court had deemed the article to contain a "detailed description of how to make a narcotic," thus classifying it as prohibited information. Roskomnadzor's justification for a full site block was pragmatic, if heavy-handed: "insofar as Wikipedia has decided to function on the basis of https, which doesn't allow restricting to individual pages on its site, the entire website would be blocked" if they did not comply. Vladimir Medeyko, director of NP Wikimedia RU, countered that the article had already been rewritten to meet the order's conditions, using scientific articles and UN documents, and attempted to preserve the content by transferring it to the article "Гашиш" ("Hashish"). [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) representatives vowed to appeal and file a complaint against Roskomnadzor if a block was enforced. In anticipation, the [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) published a resource titled "What to do if Wikipedia was blocked." On 24 August, Roskomnadzor ordered Russian internet providers to block [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia). By the night of 25 August, 10–20% of Russian users experienced access issues. However, on the very same day, the charas article was removed from the registry of banned sites after the [Federal Drug Control Service](/Federal_Drug_Control_Service_of_Russia) acknowledged that "sufficient edits were made that met the conditions of court order." <br><br> The [Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine) in February 2022 drastically escalated the information war. In the initial weeks, [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) editors alerted users to "several, reiterated attempts" by the [Putin](/Vladimir_Putin)-led Russian government to engage in [political censorship](/Political_censorship), [Internet propaganda](/Internet_manipulation), [disinformation](/Disinformation_in_the_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine) [attacks](/Disinformation_attack), and disruptive editing, particularly targeting articles listing [Russian military casualties as well as Ukrainian civilians and children due to the ongoing war](/Casualties_of_the_Russo-Ukrainian_War). On 1 March 2022, Roskomnadzor explicitly threatened to block the [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) over its article ru:Вторжение России на Украину (2022) ("Russian invasion of Ukraine (2022)"). The regulator claimed the article contained "illegally distributed information," including "reports about numerous casualties among service personnel of the Russian Federation and also the civilian population of Ukraine, including children"—information that directly contradicted the official state narrative. <br><br> The financial penalties soon followed. On 31 March 2022, Roskomnadzor threatened [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) with a fine of up to 4 million rubles (approximately $49,000) if it failed to delete "misinforming" content about the war. In April–May 2022, several [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) articles were added to [Russia](/Russia)'s list of forbidden sites, including "2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine," "[Ruscism](/Ruscism)," several articles detailing military actions and [war crimes during the Russian invasion of Ukraine](/War_crimes_in_the_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine), and even two sections within the [Russian Wikipedia](/Russian_Wikipedia) article about [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) himself. <br><br> On 20 July 2022, in a further attempt to isolate [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), [Roskomnadzor](/Roskomnadzor) ordered Russian search engines to label [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) as a "violator of Russian laws" due to its refusal to remove articles about the war. The fines continued to mount: on 1 November 2022, the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) was fined 2 million rubles, and again on 13 April 2023, by a Russian court for its steadfast refusal to delete the contested articles. <br><br> The crackdown extended to individuals and organizations. In December 2023, Stanislav Kozlovsky, the director of Wikimedia Russia, was officially designated as a "[foreign agent](/Russian_foreign_agent_law)" by the Justice Ministry of [Russia](/Russia). This designation, a tool often used to silence dissent, led to his expulsion from Moscow University, where he taught. Consequently, Wikimedia Russia was forced to disband, effectively dismantling the local support structure for the platform. <br><br> In February 2024, Russian presidential aide [Vladimir Medinsky](/Vladimir_Medinsky) offered a revealing perspective, suggesting that while 99% of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) articles were "absolutely neutral and even interesting," a crucial 1% constituted "enemy slander." He then openly advocated for the creation of a "native Russian online encyclopedia alternative" that would supposedly be based on [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia)'s content but presumably with that "enemy slander" surgically removed. This underscores the government's dual strategy: suppress inconvenient truths on existing platforms while simultaneously attempting to build state-controlled alternatives that present a curated, sanitized version of reality. |
| [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) | 2000s–present &#91; [needs update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers) &#93; | Partial &#91; [needs update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers) &#93; | Select pages | Yes | Yes | The Kingdom of [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) has a long-standing practice of [Internet censorship in Saudi Arabia](/Internet_censorship_in_Saudi_Arabia), often citing moral and religious grounds, but frequently extending to politically sensitive content. [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has not been immune to these restrictions. On 11 July 2006, the Saudi government imposed a block on both [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) and [Google Translate](/Google_Translate). The stated reason was the presence of sexual and politically sensitive content. [Google Translate](/Google_Translate) was included in the ban because users were cleverly employing it to bypass existing filters by translating blocked sites, a testament to the ingenuity of those seeking information. <br><br> While [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) is generally accessible in [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) today, specific pages were reportedly censored as recently as 2011, with examples including an article discussing the theory of evolution, a topic often contentious in conservative religious contexts. However, the widespread adoption of [encrypted](/Encryption) connections over [HTTPS](/HTTPS) has made this kind of surgical, page-specific censorship significantly more challenging for authorities. Currently, there is no public evidence to suggest that individual [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) pages are still being selectively blocked by the Saudi government, though the broader surveillance landscape remains opaque. <br><br> A more alarming development emerged in September 2020, revealing a deeper, more insidious form of control. Two [Wikipedia volunteer administrators](/Wikipedia_administrators) were arrested on the same day: [Osama Khalid](/Osama_Khalid) was sentenced to a staggering 32 years in prison, while [Ziyad al-Sofiani](/Censorship_in_Saudi_Arabia) received an eight-year sentence. These arrests were reported by Smex, a Lebanese NGO advocating for self-regulating information societies in the Arab world, and [Democracy for the Arab World Now](/Democracy_for_the_Arab_World_Now). A subsequent investigation by the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) itself uncovered a network of 16 users who appeared to be routinely engaging in [conflict-of-interest editing](/Conflict-of-interest_editing_on_Wikipedia). Crucially, these users were reportedly spying for the Saudi government, feeding information back to authorities and attempting to manipulate content to align with state narratives. This incident exposed a disturbing blend of direct repression and covert digital influence, demonstrating the lengths to which some governments will go to control the flow of information, even within a global, volunteer-driven project. |
| [Syria](/Syria) | 30 April 2008 – 13 February 2009 | | Arabic | | Yes | [Syria](/Syria), under the Ba'athist regime, has a history of stringent [Internet censorship in Ba'athist Syria](/Internet_censorship_in_Ba%27athist_Syria), and [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has experienced its share of these restrictions. Notably, access to the [Arabic Wikipedia](/Arabic_Wikipedia) was completely blocked in [Syria](/Syria) for a significant period between 30 April 2008 and 13 February 2009. Curiously, during this time, other language editions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) remained accessible, suggesting a targeted effort to control information specifically within the Arabic-speaking sphere, perhaps due to its direct relevance to local political and social discourse. <br><br> The human cost of online activism and contributing to open-source projects like [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) in [Syria](/Syria) is tragically underscored by the case of [Bassel Khartabil](/Bassel_Khartabil). Khartabil (باسل خرطبيل in [Arabic](/Arabic_language)) was a dedicated contributor to numerous open-source initiatives, including [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia). His arrest in 2012 was widely believed to be directly linked to his online activities and his commitment to free knowledge. In a grim conclusion to his ordeal, he was executed at [Adra Prison](/Adra_Prison) near [Damascus](/Damascus) in 2015. His fate serves as a stark reminder of the extreme risks faced by those who champion digital freedom in repressive states. In his honor, several organizations, including the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation), established the Bassel Khartabil Free Culture Fellowship in 2017, initially for a period of three years, to continue his legacy of promoting open culture and knowledge. |
| [Tunisia](/Tunisia) | 23–27 November 2006 | | All versions | | | The brief, yet significant, blockade of the [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) website in [Tunisia](/Tunisia) between 23 and 27 November 2006 serves as a historical footnote in the country's broader narrative of [Internet censorship in Tunisia](/Internet_censorship_in_Tunisia). While the duration was short, the incident highlighted the Tunisian government's willingness to block access to global information platforms when deemed necessary. This particular block, affecting all versions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), occurred during a period when the government was known for its tight control over online content, frequently filtering websites that contained political criticism, independent news, or content deemed morally objectionable. The swift, albeit temporary, disappearance of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) from Tunisian screens was a clear demonstration of state authority over the digital realm, a precursor to the greater struggles for freedom of expression that would later characterize the region. |
| [Turkey](/Turkey) | 2014–2015 (partial), April 2017–January 2020 (full) | | All versions | | | [Turkey](/Turkey)'s relationship with [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) has been, to put it mildly, tumultuous, culminating in a protracted, full-site block that garnered international attention, as detailed in the main article [Block of Wikipedia in Turkey](/Block_of_Wikipedia_in_Turkey). <br><br> In the early hours of 29 April 2017, the monitoring group [Turkey Blocks](/Turkey_Blocks) reported a complete loss of access to all language editions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) throughout [Turkey](/Turkey). This comprehensive block was initiated after Turkish authorities demanded that [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) "remove content by writers supporting terror and of linking Turkey to terror groups." The government asserted that it had not received a satisfactory response to this demand, leading to the drastic measure. <br><br> Prior to this full blockade, [Turkey](/Turkey) had already engaged in more targeted censorship. Starting on 17 November 2014, specific articles on the [Turkish Wikipedia](/Turkish_Wikipedia) had been censored. Examples included "2015 Türkiye genel seçim anketleri" ("2015 Turkey general election polls") and articles related to reproductive organs. These earlier instances of censorship lacked formal court decisions, leading to confusion and speculation. One Turkish internet provider, [TTNET](/TTNET), even suggested that [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) was simply "broken," a claim swiftly refuted by [Katherine Maher](/Katherine_Maher) from the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation), who clarified that the issue was indeed censorship. <br><br> The 2017 full block, however, dragged on for over two and a half years. It was only in December 2019 that the [Constitutional Court of Turkey](/Constitutional_Court_of_Turkey) finally intervened, ruling that the prolonged block was unconstitutional, a significant victory for freedom of information. On 15 January 2020, the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) confirmed that access to the website was being restored across [Turkey](/Turkey), ending a long period of informational isolation for Turkish users. <br><br> Wikinews has related news: <br> • Turkey blocks Wikipedia, alleging smear campaign |
