| [Venezuela](/Venezuela) | 12–18 January 2019 | | All versions | | | The blocking of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) in [Venezuela](/Venezuela) in early 2019 was a stark indicator of escalating [Censorship in Venezuela](/Censorship_in_Venezuela) and tightening governmental control over information, directly coinciding with a period of intense political instability. This incident is further elaborated in the main article [Block of Wikipedia in Venezuela](/Block_of_Wikipedia_in_Venezuela). <br><br> On the evening of 12 January 2019, [NetBlocks](/NetBlocks), an internet observatory, gathered compelling technical evidence confirming the blocking of all editions of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) within [Venezuela](/Venezuela). These restrictions were implemented by [CANTV](/CANTV), the nation's largest [telecommunications provider in the country](/Telecommunications_in_Venezuela), a state-owned entity. [NetBlocks](/NetBlocks) identified a major network disruption that affected crucial telecommunications infrastructure, occurring simultaneously with other restrictions that severely hampered Venezuelans' ability to communicate and access information over the preceding 24 hours. <br><br> The data collected also revealed that a number of local websites had been recently restricted, strongly suggesting that the [recent political instability](/Crisis_in_Venezuela) was the underlying catalyst for what appeared to be a rapidly tightening regime of internet control. [Haaretz](/Haaretz) reported that the block occurred after [Nicolás Maduro](/Nicol%C3%A1s_Maduro) was "ousted" from an article on [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), referring to edits that reflected the opposition's view that he was no longer the legitimate president. This incident underscored how quickly a global, open platform could become a battleground for competing political narratives, leading to drastic measures by a government intent on controlling public perception. The block, which lasted for several days, effectively cut off a significant portion of the Venezuelan populace from a critical source of information during a period of national crisis, demonstrating the direct link between political upheaval and digital repression. |

### Single-article disputes

Beyond the broad, often clumsy, efforts to block entire platforms, governments and other powerful entities also engage in more targeted skirmishes: the single-article dispute. These battles, while seemingly minor in scale, reveal the granular level at which narratives are contested and suppressed.

#### Types of disputes

These disputes often arise from a specific kind of digital paranoia, where a single piece of information is deemed too dangerous, too defamatory, or too revealing. The motivations are varied, but the underlying fear of uncontrolled information remains constant. Governments might claim an article reveals the location of a secret military installation (as seen in [France](/France)), while individuals or corporations might allege [defamation](/Defamation) or the spread of misinformation (a common theme in [Germany](/Germany) and [India](/India)). Even the subjective judgment that an image in an article is pornographic can trigger a block, as exemplified by a case in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). These instances highlight the vulnerability of open platforms to legal challenges and the sometimes-arbitrary nature of content control.

#### Examples by country

##### [Australia](/Australia)

In 2018, [Australia](/Australia) found itself embroiled in a unique legal challenge to information dissemination. [County Court of Victoria](/County_Court_of_Victoria) chief judge [Peter Kidd](/Peter_Kidd) issued a sweeping non-publication order on all evidence and the verdict in the high-profile trial of Australian Cardinal [George Pell](/George_Pell). The suppression order was incredibly broad, applying "in all Australian states and territories" and, crucially, "on any website or other electronic or broadcast format accessible within Australia." This explicitly included [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), which, while cited, was not formally charged or directly ordered to remove content. The order created a peculiar situation where information widely available internationally was legally suppressed within [Australia](/Australia), testing the boundaries of national jurisdiction over global digital content and leaving Australian readers and editors in a challenging position regarding compliance.

##### [France](/France)

The incident involving the [Pierre-sur-Haute military radio station](/Pierre-sur-Haute_military_radio_station) on the [French Wikipedia](/French_Wikipedia) in April 2013 is a textbook case of the [Streisand effect](/Streisand_effect) in action, showcasing the futility of clumsy attempts at censorship. This particular episode drew the unwanted attention of the [French interior intelligence agency](/General_Directorate_for_Internal_Security) (DCRI), which demanded the article's removal. <br><br> The DCRI's approach was, to put it mildly, heavy-handed. They summoned [Rémi Mathis](/R%C3%A9mi_Mathis), a [volunteer administrator](/Wikipedia_administrators) of the [French Wikipedia](/French_Wikipedia) and a resident of [France](/France), to their offices on 4 April 2013. Under duress, Mathis was coerced into deleting the article. He was explicitly told that he would be held in custody and prosecuted if he did not comply. Despite Mathis explaining that this was not how [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) operates—that content is collaborative and not controlled by a single individual—he had no choice but to comply. He then warned other [sysops](/Sysop) that attempting to undelete the article would "engage their responsibility before the law." It's worth noting that Mathis had no prior connection to the article, having never edited it and not even being aware of its existence before his summons. He was targeted simply because he was easily identifiable due to his public promotion of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) and Wikimedia projects in [France](/France). <br><br> The [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) attempted to engage with the DCRI, asking which specific parts of the article were problematic. They pointed out that the article's content closely mirrored information from a 2004 documentary produced by Télévision Loire 7, a French local television station, which was freely available online. The DCRI, however, refused to provide these details, simply reiterating their demand for deletion. <br><br> The DCRI's clumsy attempt at suppression backfired spectacularly. The article was quickly restored by another [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) contributor who, strategically, lived outside [France](/France), in Switzerland. As a direct result of the controversy, the article on the [Pierre-sur-Haute military radio station](/Pierre-sur-Haute_military_radio_station) became the most read page on the [French Wikipedia](/French_Wikipedia), rocketing to over 120,000 page views during the weekend of 6–7 April 2013. It was also rapidly translated into multiple other languages, ensuring its global dissemination. French newspaper [20 minutes](/20_minutes_(France)), [Ars Technica](/Ars_Technica), and a posting on [Slashdot](/Slashdot) all highlighted the incident as a prime example of the [Streisand effect](/Streisand_effect), where attempts to hide information only serve to draw more attention to it. The [French Ministry of the Interior](/Minister_of_the_Interior_(France)) predictably declined to comment on the incident. <br><br> A judicial source, quoted by [Agence France-Presse](/Agence_France-Presse) (AFP) on 8 April, later clarified that the deletion was part of a "preliminary inquiry" by the "anti-terrorist section of the Paris prosecutor's office." The justification given was that the article compromised "classified material related to the chain of transmission for nuclear launch orders." <br><br> Following the debacle, Télévision Loire 7, the source of the original documentary, stated they expected the DCRI to request its removal, despite it having been filmed and broadcast with the full cooperation of the French armed forces. The National Union of [Police Commissioners](/Commissaire_de_police) even suggested that the next step would be for the judiciary to order French [Internet service providers](/Internet_service_provider) to block access to the [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) article, a further escalation. However, the [France](/France)-based [NGO](/Non-governmental_organization) [Reporters Without Borders](/Reporters_Without_Borders) sharply criticized the DCRI's actions as "a bad precedent," arguing that if classified information was genuinely compromised, the judiciary should be involved to assess the reality and extent of military secrecy, rather than coercing volunteers. They reiterated that hosts and intermediaries should not be held responsible for information sourced from publicly available, even officially sanctioned, documentaries. The entire episode served as a stark lesson in the counterproductive nature of heavy-handed information control.

##### [Germany](/Germany)

In a notable case in [Germany](/Germany), [Wikipedia.de](/Wikimedia_Deutschland), an internet domain operated by [Wikimedia Deutschland](/Wikimedia_Deutschland), found itself in a legal bind. A temporary injunction was issued, prohibiting the domain from redirecting to the actual [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) content. This legal action was initiated by politician [Lutz Heilmann](/Lutz_Heilmann), who took issue with claims made in a [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) article regarding his past involvement with the former [German Democratic Republic](/East_Germany)'s intelligence service, the [Stasi](/Stasi). The injunction, while not blocking the content itself, effectively severed the most obvious entry point for German users, demonstrating how legal challenges can disrupt access to information even without a direct content deletion order. It was a subtle, yet effective, way to make inconvenient facts harder to find.

##### [India](/India)

The [India](/India)n legal system once again intervened with [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) content on 21 October 2024. As previously detailed, the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) was compelled to suspend access to a specific article on the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia) that concerned the ongoing [defamation](/Defamation) lawsuit filed by [Asian News International](/Asian_News_International) (ANI) against the foundation itself. This action was taken due to an order from the [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court), which deemed the article in violation of the [sub judice](/Sub_judice) principle, essentially prohibiting public discussion of a matter still under judicial review. This marked a significant, albeit temporary, instance of content suppression on the platform in [India](/India). <br><br> However, the legal trajectory of this dispute saw a definitive change. On 9 May 2025, the [Supreme Court of India](/Supreme_Court_of_India), acting on an appeal, overturned the [Delhi High Court](/Delhi_High_Court)'s order that mandated the takedown of the page. The Supreme Court's ruling emphasized the crucial role of a free media in a liberal democracy and asserted that it is not the judiciary's prerogative to instruct media organizations to delete or remove content, even if it is critical of them. This decision led to the restoration of the article, affirming principles of [press freedom](/Freedom_of_the_press) and open information in the face of legal pressures.

##### [Portugal](/Portugal)

Following a court order issued in August 2025 by the Portuguese [Supreme Court of Justice](/Supreme_Court_of_Justice_(Portugal)), specific sections of the English and Portuguese [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) articles concerning businessman [Caesar DePaço](/Caesar_DePa%C3%A7o) were subjected to partial censorship. This action was taken to ensure compliance with the court's decree, highlighting how national legal systems can compel global platforms to modify content based on local judgments, even if it means altering a publicly accessible, collaborative encyclopedia. The specifics of the content removed were not broadly publicized, but the precedent of judicial intervention on a global platform remains.

##### [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)

The [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) has its own peculiar history with [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) censorship, notably involving the [Internet Watch Foundation](/Internet_Watch_Foundation) (IWF), a UK-based [non-government organization](/Non-government_organization) responsible for blacklisting child sexual abuse imagery. This incident is further explored in [Internet censorship in the United Kingdom](/Internet_censorship_in_the_United_Kingdom) and [Internet Watch Foundation and Wikipedia](/Internet_Watch_Foundation_and_Wikipedia). <br><br> In December 2008, the IWF made the rather controversial decision to add the [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) article [Virgin Killer](/Virgin_Killer) to its internet [blacklist](/Blacklisting). The reason? The album cover's image, which depicts a pre-pubescent girl, and the perceived illegality of [child pornography](/Child_pornography) in the UK. The IWF had assessed the image as being at the "lowest level of legal concern," categorizing it as "erotic posing with no sexual activity." Despite this nuanced classification, the inclusion on the blacklist had immediate and widespread consequences. <br><br> As a direct result, individuals using many major UK [ISPs](/Internet_service_provider) found themselves blocked from viewing the *entire* article by the [Cleanfeed](/Cleanfeed_(content_blocking_system)) system, a national content blocking system. Even more significantly, a large portion of the UK's internet users were inadvertently blocked from editing *any* part of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia). This collateral damage occurred because of the technical means the IWF employed to block the image, which often involved blocking the IP addresses of the servers hosting the content, thereby affecting all users connected through those servers. <br><br> The decision sparked a considerable public outcry and extensive discussion. The [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation) made strong representations, and public complaints flooded in. Recognizing the significant overreach and unintended consequences of their action, the IWF reversed their decision three days later. They also provided an assurance that, in the future, they would not block copies of similar images that were hosted overseas, acknowledging the impracticality and censorship implications of such broad-brush blocking. This incident served as a powerful illustration of how well-intentioned censorship efforts can lead to disproportionate restrictions on legitimate content and free expression, even within a country generally considered to have robust freedoms.

